<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1886-07-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1886-07-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="266" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d266">
                        <head>No. 262.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Boutelle</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department, of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1886-07-15"><hi rend="italic">July</hi> 15,
                                1886</date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have your letter dated yesterday
                            enclosing the affidavit of Stephen R. Balkam, relating the circumstances
                            of his being ordered away from St. Andrews, New Brunswick, by the
                            Dominion cruiser Middleton, Captain Kent, in July 9th instant, and the
                            refusal by Captain Kent to allow thq deponent to purchase fish caught
                            and sold by Canadians for canning.</p>
                        <p>The affidavit shall be placed on file for reference.</p>
                        <p>Yours, &amp;c.,</p>
                        <closer><signed>T. F. BAYARD.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>